SIMPLE: progress
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Progress
<hw>Prog"ress</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>progressus</ets>, from <ets>progredi</ets>, p. p.
<ets>progressus</ets>, to go forth or forward; <ets>pro</ets> forward +
<ets>gradi</ets> to step, go: cf. F. <ets>progr⟦egrave⟧s</ets>. See
<er>Grade</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- each subdefinition implicitly begins with "a moving forward . . .
" --> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A moving or going forward; a proceeding onward;
an advance</def>; specifically: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>In actual space, as
the <xex>progress</xex> of a ship, carriage, etc.</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>In the growth of an animal or plant; increase.</def> <sd>(c)</sd>
<def>In business of any kind; <as>as, the <ex>progress</ex> of a
negotiation; the <ex>progress</ex> of art.</as></def> <sd>(d)</sd>
<def>In knowledge; in proficiency; <as>as, the <ex>progress</ex> of a
child at school</as>.</def> <sd>(e)</sd> <def>Toward ideal completeness
or perfection in respect of quality or condition; -- applied to
individuals, communities, or the race; <as>as, social, moral, religious,
or political <ex>progress</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A journey of state; a circuit; especially, one made
by a sovereign through parts of his own dominions.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The king being returned from his <qex>progresse</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj><-- sic. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Progress</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Progress
<hw>Pro*gress"</hw> <pr>(?; <xex>formerly pronounced like</xex>
<er>Progress</er>, <pos>n.</pos>)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Progressed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>;
<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Progressing</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To make progress; to move forward in space; to
continue onward in course; to proceed; to advance; to go on; <as>as,
railroads are <ex>progressing</ex></as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧As his recovery
<xex>progressed</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let me wipe off this honorable dew,⟦br⟧
That silverly doth <qex>progress</qex> on thy checks.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>progress</qex> in that style in proportion as their
pieces are treated with contempt.</q>
<rj><qau>Washington.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The war had <qex>progressed</qex> for some time.</q>
<rj><qau>Marshall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make improvement; to advance.</def>
<rj><au>Bayard.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If man <qex>progresses</qex>, art must <qex>progress</qex>
too.</q> <rj><qau>Caird.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Progress</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Progress
<hw>Prog"ress</hw> <pr>(?; see <er>Progress</er>, <pos>v.
i.</pos>)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make progress in; to pass
through.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Progression</ent>⟦br⟧
